<org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-Pk1oHSINsYCqa7h4OGuAtA" name="reference_architecture_fit_gap_analysis,_5oXdMDDHEdyz_pzDMsV8FQ" guid="-Pk1oHSINsYCqa7h4OGuAtA" changeDate="2007-11-16T08:53:23.000-0800" version="v.2">
  <purpose>This artifact is used as the basis for deciding whether a reference architecture should be used or not and indicates any&#xD;
gaps where the reference architecture does not support the system requirements.</purpose>
  <impactOfNotHaving>If a reference architecture fit-gap analysis is not performed then an incorrect or inappropriate reference architecture may&#xD;
be selected or the costs associated with adapting a reference architecture may be underestimated.</impactOfNotHaving>
  <reasonsForNotNeeding>&lt;p>&#xD;
    It may not be appropriate to produce this artifact if:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The solution is in an area where no reference architectures exist or can be found.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The system being built is trivial and the use of a reference architecture would be too costly or otherwise&#xD;
        inappropriate.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        There is a clear statement made by the stakeholder that reference architectures should not be used.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The decision to use the reference architecture is straightforward and doesn't require a fit-gap analysis.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The fit will be evaluated through another approach, such as prototyping.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></reasonsForNotNeeding>
  <briefOutline>&lt;p>&#xD;
    This work product typically contains:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Executive Summary - A brief summary of the analysis, the recommendation and major issues identified.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Introduction - Sets the context of this analysis and identifies the reference architecture that is being used to&#xD;
        compare against.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Key Drivers - Summarize the business drivers for the system.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Architecture Requirements Checklist - The major requirements (functional and non-functional) to be considered when&#xD;
        performing the fit-gap analysis.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Subject Area Checklist: Subject areas, or domains, are the major subsystems present in the reference architecture.&#xD;
        Content management, e-mail, enterprise application integration etc are examples of subject areas which may be&#xD;
        present in a reference architecture.&amp;nbsp; One way of testing the &quot;fit&quot; to a reference architecture is to compare&#xD;
        subject areas between the reference architecture and the new system, if they are known.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Statement of Fit: A list or table which describes the gaps between the reference architecture and the new system by&#xD;
        comparing requirements and/or subject areas. Record here:&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li style=&quot;LIST-STYLE-TYPE: none&quot;>&#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                The requirement and/or subject area.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                The degree of fit and how the system could be adapted if it is to use the reference architecture.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Costs and risks associated with adapting the system to use the reference architecture or not.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></briefOutline>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
